{"title_page": "Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch", "text_new": "{{infobox officeholder\n| name         =\n| image        = Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch.jpg\n| office       = [[List of ambassadors of Germany to Italy|German Ambassador to Italy]]\n| monarch      = [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm II]]\n| term_start   = 1897\n| term_end     = 1899\n| predecessor  = [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]]\n| successor    = [[Karl von Wedel]]\n| office1      = [[List of ambassadors of Germany to the United States|German Ambassador to the United States]]\n| monarch1     = [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm II]]\n| term_start1  = 1893\n| term_end1    = 1895\n| predecessor1 = [[Theodor von Holleben]] <small>(as Minister Plenipotentiary)</small>\n| successor1   = [[Max von Thielmann]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1836|03|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Zagrodno|Adelsdorf]]\n| death_date   = {{dda|1900|04|28|1836|03|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Chr\u00f3stnik|Brauchitschdorf]]\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Bonn]]\n| parents      = Margarete von Hatzfeld zu Wildenburg\n| spouse       =\n| relations    =\n}}\n\nFreiherr '''Johann Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch''' (27 March 1836 \u2013 28 April 1900)<ref name=\"NYTObit1900\"/> was a German aristocrat and diplomat.\n\n==Early life==\nAnton was born on 27 March 1836 in [[Zagrodno|Adelsdorf]], [[Germany]] (today part of south-western [[Poland]]). He was a son of [[Freiherr]] Johann ''Alexander'' Saurma von der Jeltsch-Lorzendorf (1804\u20131841) and the former [[Freifrau]] Marie ''Luise'' Antonie Anna Franziska von Frankenberg und Ludwigsdorf (1807\u20131876). His older brother was Johann Josef ''Arthur'' Saurma von der Jeltsch-Lorzendorf, who married Laura \"Lory\" [[Henckel von Donnersmarck]] (a daughter of [[Hugo Henckel von Donnersmarck]]). His younger brother was the prominent [[numismatist]] Hugo von Saurma von der Jeltsch.<ref name=\"Harrison1914\">{{cite book |last1=of) |first1=Melville Amadeus Henry Douglas Heddle de La Caillemotte de Massue de Ruvigny Ruvigny and Raineval (9th marquis |title=The Titled Nobility of Europe: An International Peerage, Or \"Who's Who\", of the Sovereigns, Princes and Nobles of Europe |date=1914 |publisher=Harrison & Sons |page=1312 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PUm1lS2j-wQC&pg=PA1312&lpg=PA1312 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis paternal grandparents were Freiherr Johann Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch and Aloysia [[Gr\u00e4fin]] von Hoverden-Plencken. His maternal grandparents were Count Joseph von Frankenberg, Baron von Schellendorf, heir to [[Warta Boles\u0142awiecka|Warthau]] and Countess Maria Theresia von Frankenberg (an supporter of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]]).<ref name=\"Harrison1914\"/><ref name=\"Abert2007\">{{cite book |last1=Abert |first1=Hermann |title=W.A. Mozart |date=2007 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-07223-5 |page=1508 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l6I6BwTMJ3sC&pg=PA1508&lpg=PA1508 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe studied law at the [[University of Bonn]].<ref name=\"Bettelheim1903\">{{cite book |last1=Bettelheim |first1=Anton |title=Biographisches Jahrbuch und Deutscher Nekrolog |date=1903 |publisher=Georg Reimer |page=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nxANAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA5-PT3&lpg=RA5-PT3 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe entered the diplomatic service in 1850, eventually becoming ''[[attach\u00e9]]'' in Paris.<ref name=\"Burke1901\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Edmund |title=The Annual Register |date=1901 |publisher=Rivingtons |page=127 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Annual_Register/VScNAAAAIAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Alexander+Saurma+von+der+Jeltsch&pg=RA1-PA127 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  In 1866, he took part in the [[Austro-Prussian War]] as a Prussian army officer. After the war, he managed the business of various legations and in 1872 he became a legation councilor. In 1873, he was appointed embassy councilor in [[Constantinople]] and in 1875, he became German [[Consul-General]] in [[Belgrade]],<ref name=\"Bringmann2012\">{{cite book |last1=Bringmann |first1=Tobias C. |title=Handbuch der Diplomatie 1815-1963: Ausw\u00e4rtige Missionschefs in Deutschland und deutsche Missionschefs im Ausland von Metternich bis Adenauer |date=2012 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-11-095684-9 |page=73 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pXWJpFbz1AoC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |language=de}}</ref> followed by Consul-General and diplomatic agent to [[Egypt]] and based in [[Alexandria]] in 1879.<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>\n\nIn 1882, he became [[List of ambassadors of Germany to Romania|German Ambassador]] to the [[Kingdom of Romania]] in [[Bucharest]] and, in 1885, to the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] in [[The Hague]].<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>  In 1891, he became a Prussian envoy to the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]] in [[Stuttgart]].<ref name=\"R\u00f6hl2004\">{{cite book |last1=R\u00f6hl |first1=John C. G. |title=Wilhelm II: The Kaiser's Personal Monarchy, 1888-1900 |date=2004 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-81920-6 |page=958 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Wilhelm_II/lkqh9UV3yvUC?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Anton+Saurma+von+der+Jeltsch&pg=PA958 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  In 1893,<ref name=\"1893Arrival\">{{cite news |title=DELIGHTED WITH NEW-YORK; GERMANY'S AMBASSADOR VISITS ITS BUSY STREETS. Baron von Saurma-Jeltsh's First Visit to the United States -- He Takes a Look at the Stock Exchange and Visits the Post Office -- Impressed by the Building's in Broadway -- Soon to Visit the World's Fair -- The Baron Thinks the Sherman Law Should Be Repealed. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1893/08/25/archives/delighted-with-newyork-germanys-ambassador-visits-its-busy-streets.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 August 1893}}</ref> he became the first [[List of ambassadors of Germany to the United States|German Ambassador to the United States]], replacing Minister [[Theodor von Holleben|Baron von Holleben]], who took his old post in Stuttgart.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|In August 1897, [[Theodor von Holleben|Baron Theodor von Holleben]] returned to Washington as the [[List of ambassadors of Germany to the United States|German Ambassador to the United States]], replacing [[Max von Thielmann]], Baron Saurma's successor.<ref name=\"1897USAppointment\">{{cite news |title=NEW GERMAN AMBASSADOR.; Dr. von Holleben, Prussian Minister at Stuttgart, to Represent His Country in Washington. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/08/27/archives/new-german-ambassador-dr-von-holleben-prussian-minister-at.html?searchResultPosition=9 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 August 1897}}</ref>}}  Before taking his post in [[Washington, D.C.]], he traveled to [[New York City]] with Baron [[Clemens von Ketteler]], the Counselor and First Secretary to the German Embassy, where they toured the city, visiting the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and the [[obelisk]] known as [[Cleopatra's Needle (New York City)|Cleopatra's Needle]] in [[Central Park]], which he had seen while stationed in Egypt.<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>  In Washington, the Ambassador resided at 1435 Massachusetts Avenue which was bought by the German government a few months before his arrival.<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>  In November 1894, he was among the guests who dined with President [[Grover Cleveland|Cleveland]]'s [[Solicitor General of the United States|Solicitor General]] [[Lawrence Maxwell Jr.]], including [[Secretary of State]] [[Walter Q. Gresham]] and [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Stephen Johnson Field]].<ref name=\"1894Dine\">{{cite news |title=Dined with the Solicitor General |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1894/12/01/archives/dined-with-the-solicitor-general-three-persons-burned-to-death.html?searchResultPosition=18 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1 December 1894}}</ref> In 1895, he was replaced by [[Max von Thielmann]].<ref name=\"1895Change\">{{cite news |title=GERMANY TO CHANGE AMBASSADORS; And Argentine Will Have a New Representative Temporarily. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/03/27/archives/germany-to-change-ambassadors-and-argentine-will-have-a-new.html?searchResultPosition=27 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 March 1895}}</ref><ref name=\"1895Replacement\">{{cite news |title=VON THIELMAN, GERMAN AMBASSADOR; He Takes the Place Vacated by Baron von Saurma-Jelstch. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/06/22/archives/von-thielman-german-ambassador-he-takes-the-place-vacated-by-baron.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=22 June 1895}}</ref><ref name=\"1895Surprise\">{{cite news |title=A SURPRISE FOR GERMANY; The Franco-Russian Loan to China Upsets Calculations. BERLIN FINANCIERS DISAPPOINTED Strenuous Efforts Will Be Made to Secure for Them a Large Share of the Main Indemnity Loan That China Must Negotiate. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/06/10/archives/a-surprise-for-germany-the-francorussian-loan-to-china-upsets.html?searchResultPosition=3 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 June 1895}}</ref>\n\nIn 1895, he returned to Constantinople to serve as German Ambassador to the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"Ihrig2016\"/> In his report about the treatment of the [[Armenian Genocide|Armenians]],<ref name=\"1896Warning\">{{cite news |title=GERMANY WARNS TURKEY; ATROCPTIES IN CRETE, IF CONTINUED, WILL LEAD TO TROUBLE. The Sultan Told that He May Lose the Good Will of the Powers--Demand for the Autonomy of Macedonia--The Sultan's III Health--A Woman Spendthrift--Prince Furstenberg's Illness--Another Scandal in Society. The Sultan's III Health. A Woman Spendthrift. Lenient to an Englishman. Foreigh Residents in Prussia. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1896/06/15/archives/germany-warns-turkey-atrocpties-in-crete-if-continued-will-lead-to.html?searchResultPosition=17 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 June 1896}}</ref><ref name=\"1896Armenian\">{{cite news |title=ARMENIAN HOMES BURNED; Nearly 200 Towns and Villages Destroyed in Two Provinces. THOUSANDS OF PERSONS WERE SLAIN Figures on the Destructive Work of the Turks -- The Sultan Receives Two Foreign Ambassadors. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1896/01/13/archives/armenian-homes-burned-nearly-200-towns-and-villages-destroyed-in.html?searchResultPosition=13 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=13 January 1896}}</ref> Anton:<ref name=\"Ihrig2016\">{{cite book |last1=Ihrig |first1=Stefan |title=Justifying Genocide: Germany and the Armenians from Bismark to Hitler |date=2016 |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |isbn=978-0-674-91517-6 |page=37 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Justifying_Genocide/PARuCwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Anton+Saurma+von+der+Jeltsch&pg=PA37 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\"stressed how nonsensical he found both the demonstration and the demands of the Armenians, drew particular attention to the role of the police force. He wrote that the police did not only tolerate 'that the population was massacring the Armenians, but was cheering them on and took part itself in the slaughtering of already heavily wounded and tied-up Armenians.' He also described how \"Armenians were then even 'raided and slaughtered' in their own homes.\"<ref name=\"Ihrig2016\"/></blockquote>\n\nHe was replaced in Constantinople by Baron [[Adolf Marschall von Bieberstein]], the former [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|German Minister for Foreign Affairs]], in 1897.<ref name=\"1897Post\">{{cite news |title=VON BIEBERSTEIN'S NEW POST.; The Sultan Assents to His Appointment to Succeed Baron Jeltsch. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/10/20/archives/von-biebersteins-new-post-the-sultan-assents-to-his-appointment-to.html?searchResultPosition=5 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 October 1897}}</ref><ref name=\"1897Shelved\">{{cite news |title=VON BIEBERSTEIN SHELVED.; Will Go to Turkey as Ambassador The Sultan Feels the Compliment. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/10/21/archives/von-bieberstein-shelved-will-go-to-turkey-as-ambassador-the-sultan.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=21 October 1897}}</ref>  From 1897 to 1899, he was the [[List of ambassadors of Germany to Italy|German Ambassador to Italy]] in [[Rome]], where he replaced [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]] who succeeded von Bieberstein as the Emperor's Minister for Foreign Affairs. Saurma von der Jeltsch retired in 1899, shortly before his death in April 1900.<ref name=\"Harrison1914\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnton was married to Margarete [[House of Hatzfeld|von Hatzfeld zu Wildenburg]] (1850\u20131923), a daughter of Pauline [[House of Castellane|de Castellane]] and Count [[Max von Hatzfeld]],<ref name=\"1911Nobles\">{{cite news |last1=Diplomat |first1=A. Veteran |title=SOME EUROPEAN NOBLES THAT ARE ALMOST AMERICANS; The Family Histories of Prince Hermann Hatzfeldt and Baroness Stumm, Who Are Soon to Wed, Show Their Close Relation to This Country. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1911/03/12/archives/some-european-nobles-that-are-almost-americans-the-family-histories.html?searchResultPosition=5 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 March 1911}}</ref> who spent ten years from 1849 to 1859 as the [[List of ambassadors of Germany to France|German Minister to France]] and who signed the [[Treaty of Paris (1856)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1856 which ended the [[Crimean War]].<ref name=\"Gothaisches1906\">{{cite book |title=Gothaisches genealogisches Taschenbuch der gr\u00e4flichen H\u00e4user |date=1906 |publisher=Justus Perthes. |page=749 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4sITAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA749&lpg=PA749 |accessdate=5 May 2020 |language=de}}</ref>  After her father's death, her mother remarried to [[Louis de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]], duc de Valen\u00e7ay, 3rd duc de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord.<ref name=\"Heinemann1910\">{{cite book |last1=de) |first1=Doroth\u00e9e Dino (duchesse |title=Memoirs of the Duchesse de Dino: (afterwards Duchesse de Talleyrand Et de Sagan) 1841-1850 |date=1910 |publisher=W. Heinemann |page=372 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKNGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA372&lpg=PA372 |accessdate=5 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Her elder sister, H\u00e9l\u00e8ne, was the wife of [[Georg von Kanitz]] (''aide de camp'' to [[Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia (1828\u20131885)|Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia]]).<ref name=\"Hatzfeldt1905\">{{cite book |last1=Hatzfeldt |first1=Paul Graf von |title=The Hatzfeldt Letters: Letters of Count Paul Hatzfeldt to His Wife, Written from the Head-quarters of the King of Prussia, 1870-71 |date=1905 |publisher=John Murray |page=46 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySI_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46 |accessdate=5 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Together, they were the parents of two children:<ref name=\"Quadrangle1973\">{{cite book |title=The Book of Kings: The Families |date=1973 |publisher=Quadrangle / New York Times Book Company |isbn=978-0-8129-0280-8 |page=766 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Book_of_Kings_The_families/BF0RAQAAMAAJ |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* Freiherr Maximilian Saurma von der Jeltsch (1873\u20131949), who married Anne Marie Strachwitz von Gro\u00df-Zauche und Camminetz.<ref name=\"Quadrangle1973\"/>\n* Freifrau Carmen Saurma von der Jeltsch (1875-1952), who was given a ball in Washington for her debut while her father was Ambassador.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|Among the guests at Baroness Carmen's debut at the [[Embassy of Germany, Washington, D.C.|German Embassy]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] on 8 January 1895 were the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to the United States|English Ambassador]] [[Julian Pauncefote, 1st Baron Pauncefote|Lord Pauncefort]] and Lady Pauncefote and the Misses Pauncefote, [[Hugh Gough, 3rd Viscount Gough|Hugh Gough]] and Lady Georgiana Gough (a daughter of the [[William Pakenham, 4th Earl of Longford|4th Earl of Longford]]), [[Henry Bax-Ironside|Bax Ironsides]], [[Cecil Spring Rice]], [[Mary Knowlton von Francken-Sierstorpff|Count Sierstorpff]], Baron Uechtritz, [[Salvador de Iturbide y Marz\u00e1n|Prince Iturbide]], the [[List of ambassadors of Brazil to the United States|Brazilian Minister]] and Mme. Mendon\u00e7a, the [[Turkish Ambassador to the United States|Turkish Minister]], the [[List of ambassadors of Spain to the United States|Spanish Minister]] Railie de Muruaga, and the [[List of ambassadors of Denmark to the United States|Danish Minister]] [[Constantin Brun]], the [[List of ambassadors of Italy to the United States|Italian Ambassador]] [[Saverio Fava]] and Baroness Fava, the [[Nicaragua\u2013United States relations|Nicaraguan Minister]] and Mme. Guzman, the [[List of ambassadors of the Netherlands to the United States|Netherlands Minister]] William Ferdinand Henry von Weckherlin, [[List of ambassadors of Belgium to the United States|Belgian Minister]] Count G. de Lichtervelde, and [[List of ambassadors of Sweden to the United States|Swedish Minister]] Johan Anton Wolff Grip, the [[List of ambassadors of Mexico to the United States|Mexican Minister]] [[Mat\u00edas Romero]] and Mme. Romero, Mr. and Mrs. [[Howland & Aspinwall|S. S. Howland]], [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary]] [[Hilary A. Herbert]] and Miss Herbert, Mrs. [[J. Donald Cameron|Don Cameron]] and Miss Rachel Cameron, the Misses Patten, Dr. Tavel and Mr. Vogel of the Swiss legation, [[Count Aldebert de Chambrun|Count de Chambrun]] and M. Le Favre of the [[Embassy of France, Washington, D.C.|French Embassy]], the [[List of diplomatic missions of Austria-Hungary|Austrian Minister]] [[Ladislaus Hengelm\u00fcller von Hengerv\u00e1r]] and Baroness von Hengelm\u00fcller, [[Hobart Chatfield-Taylor|Hobart]] and [[Rose Farwell Chatfield-Taylor]], Senator [[Edward O. Wolcott]] and [[Frances Metcalfe Wolcott|Mrs. Wolcott]], [[Guglielmo Imperiali|Marquis Imperiali]], Miss Biddle, [[U.S. Senator|Senator]] [[James McMillan (politician)|James McMillan]] and Mrs. and Miss McMillan, Mr. Waterbury, the Misses Boardman, [[Third Assistant Secretary of State|Assistant Secretary of State]] [[William Woodville Rockhill|Rockhill]] and Mrs. Rockhill, and Count [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Sz\u00e9chenyi|Sz\u00e9chenyi]].<ref name=\"1895Ball\"/>}}<ref name=\"1895Ball\">{{cite news |title=BARONESS VON SAURMA'S DEBUT; Grand Ball at the German Ambassador's in Washington -- The President Dines with Mr. Gresham. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/01/09/archives/baroness-von-saurmas-debut-grand-ball-at-the-german-ambassadors-in.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 January 1895}}</ref> She later married Stanislaus Graf Hoyos, Freiherr zu Stichsenstein.<ref name=\"Quadrangle1973\"/>\n\nBaron Von der Jeltsch died on 28 April 1900 in [[Chr\u00f3stnik|Brauchitschdorf]].<ref name=\"NYTObit1900\">{{cite book |title=Baron von der Jeltsch Dead. |date=1900 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1900/05/01/archives/baron-von-der-jeltsch-dead.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=6 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n;Sources\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeltsch, Anton Saurma von der}}\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:German untitled nobility]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to the Netherlands|Jeltsch]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to the United States|Jeltsch]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to Turkey|Jeltsch]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to Italy|Jeltsch]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox officeholder\n| name         =\n| image        = Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch.jpg\n| office       = [[List of ambassadors of Germany to Italy|German Ambassador to Italy]]\n| monarch      = [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm II]]\n| term_start   = 1897\n| term_end     = 1899\n| predecessor  = [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]]\n| successor    = [[Karl von Wedel]]\n| office1      = [[List of ambassadors of Germany to the United States|German Ambassador to the United States]]\n| monarch1     = [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm II]]\n| term_start1  = 1893\n| term_end1    = 1895\n| predecessor1 = [[Theodor von Holleben]] <small>(as Minister Plenipotentiary)</small>\n| successor1   = [[Max von Thielmann]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1836|03|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Zagrodno|Adelsdorf]]\n| death_date   = {{dda|1900|04|28|1836|03|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Chr\u00f3stnik|Brauchitschdorf]]\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Bonn]]\n| parents      = Margarete von Hatzfeld zu Wildenburg\n| spouse       =\n| relations    =\n}}\n\nFreiherr '''Johann Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch''' (27 March 1836 \u2013 28 April 1900)<ref name=\"NYTObit1900\"/> was a German aristocrat and diplomat.\n\n==Early life==\nAnton was born on 27 March 1836 in [[Zagrodno|Adelsdorf]], [[Germany]] (today part of south-western [[Poland]]). He was a son of [[Freiherr]] Johann ''Alexander'' Saurma von der Jeltsch-Lorzendorf (1804\u20131841) and the former [[Freifrau]] Marie ''Luise'' Antonie Anna Franziska von Frankenberg und Ludwigsdorf (1807\u20131876). His older brother was Johann Josef ''Arthur'' Saurma von der Jeltsch-Lorzendorf, who married Laura \"Lory\" [[Henckel von Donnersmarck]] (a daughter of [[Hugo Henckel von Donnersmarck]]). His younger brother was the prominent [[numismatist]] Hugo von Saurma von der Jeltsch.<ref name=\"Harrison1914\">{{cite book |last1=of) |first1=Melville Amadeus Henry Douglas Heddle de La Caillemotte de Massue de Ruvigny Ruvigny and Raineval (9th marquis |title=The Titled Nobility of Europe: An International Peerage, Or \"Who's Who\", of the Sovereigns, Princes and Nobles of Europe |date=1914 |publisher=Harrison & Sons |page=1312 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PUm1lS2j-wQC&pg=PA1312&lpg=PA1312 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis paternal grandparents were Freiherr Johann Anton Saurma von der Jeltsch and Aloysia [[Gr\u00e4fin]] von Hoverden-Plencken. His maternal grandparents were Count Joseph von Frankenberg, Baron von Schellendorf, heir to [[Warta Boles\u0142awiecka|Warthau]] and Countess Maria Theresia von Frankenberg (an supporter of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]]).<ref name=\"Harrison1914\"/><ref name=\"Abert2007\">{{cite book |last1=Abert |first1=Hermann |title=W.A. Mozart |date=2007 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-07223-5 |page=1508 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l6I6BwTMJ3sC&pg=PA1508&lpg=PA1508 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe studied law at the [[University of Bonn]].<ref name=\"Bettelheim1903\">{{cite book |last1=Bettelheim |first1=Anton |title=Biographisches Jahrbuch und Deutscher Nekrolog |date=1903 |publisher=Georg Reimer |page=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nxANAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA5-PT3&lpg=RA5-PT3 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe entered the diplomatic service in 1850, eventually becoming ''[[attach\u00e9]]'' in Paris.<ref name=\"Burke1901\">{{cite book |last1=Burke |first1=Edmund |title=The Annual Register |date=1901 |publisher=Rivingtons |page=127 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Annual_Register/VScNAAAAIAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Alexander+Saurma+von+der+Jeltsch&pg=RA1-PA127 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  In 1866, he took part in the [[Austro-Prussian War]] as a Prussian army officer. After the war, he managed the business of various legations and in 1872 he became a legation councilor. In 1873, he was appointed embassy councilor in [[Constantinople]] and in 1875, he became German [[Consul-General]] in [[Belgrade]],<ref name=\"Bringmann2012\">{{cite book |last1=Bringmann |first1=Tobias C. |title=Handbuch der Diplomatie 1815-1963: Ausw\u00e4rtige Missionschefs in Deutschland und deutsche Missionschefs im Ausland von Metternich bis Adenauer |date=2012 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-11-095684-9 |page=73 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pXWJpFbz1AoC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |language=de}}</ref> followed by Consul-General and diplomatic agent to [[Egypt]] and based in [[Alexandria]] in 1879.<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>\n\nIn 1882, he became [[List of ambassadors of Germany to Romania|German Ambassador]] to the [[Kingdom of Romania]] in [[Bucharest]] and, in 1885, to the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] in [[The Hague]].<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>  In 1891, he became a Prussian envoy to the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]] in [[Stuttgart]].<ref name=\"R\u00f6hl2004\">{{cite book |last1=R\u00f6hl |first1=John C. G. |title=Wilhelm II: The Kaiser's Personal Monarchy, 1888-1900 |date=2004 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-81920-6 |page=958 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Wilhelm_II/lkqh9UV3yvUC?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Anton+Saurma+von+der+Jeltsch&pg=PA958 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  In 1893,<ref name=\"1893Arrival\">{{cite news |title=DELIGHTED WITH NEW-YORK; GERMANY'S AMBASSADOR VISITS ITS BUSY STREETS. Baron von Saurma-Jeltsh's First Visit to the United States -- He Takes a Look at the Stock Exchange and Visits the Post Office -- Impressed by the Building's in Broadway -- Soon to Visit the World's Fair -- The Baron Thinks the Sherman Law Should Be Repealed. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1893/08/25/archives/delighted-with-newyork-germanys-ambassador-visits-its-busy-streets.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 August 1893}}</ref> he became the first [[List of ambassadors of Germany to the United States|German Ambassador to the United States]], replacing Minister [[Theodor von Holleben|Baron von Holleben]], who took his old post in Stuttgart.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|In August 1897, [[Theodor von Holleben|Baron Theodor von Holleben]] returned to Washington as the [[List of ambassadors of Germany to the United States|German Ambassador to the United States]], replacing [[Max von Thielmann]], Baron Saurma's successor.<ref name=\"1897USAppointment\">{{cite news |title=NEW GERMAN AMBASSADOR.; Dr. von Holleben, Prussian Minister at Stuttgart, to Represent His Country in Washington. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/08/27/archives/new-german-ambassador-dr-von-holleben-prussian-minister-at.html?searchResultPosition=9 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 August 1897}}</ref>}}  Before taking his post in [[Washington, D.C.]], he traveled to [[New York City]] with Baron [[Clemens von Ketteler]], the Counselor and First Secretary to the German Embassy, where they toured the city, visiting the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and the [[obelisk]] known as [[Cleopatra's Needle (New York City)|Cleopatra's Needle]] in [[Central Park]], which he had seen while stationed in Egypt.<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>  In Washington, the Ambassador resided at 1435 Massachusetts Avenue which was bought by the German government a few months before his arrival.<ref name=\"1893Arrival\"/>  In November 1894, he was among the guests who dined with President [[Grover Cleveland|Cleveland]]'s [[Solicitor General of the United States|Solicitor General]] [[Lawrence Maxwell Jr.]], including [[Secretary of State]] [[Walter Q. Gresham|Walter Q. Gresham]] and [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Stephen Johnson Field]].<ref name=\"1894Dine\">{{cite news |title=Dined with the Solicitor General |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1894/12/01/archives/dined-with-the-solicitor-general-three-persons-burned-to-death.html?searchResultPosition=18 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1 December 1894}}</ref> In 1895, he was replaced by [[Max von Thielmann]].<ref name=\"1895Change\">{{cite news |title=GERMANY TO CHANGE AMBASSADORS; And Argentine Will Have a New Representative Temporarily. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/03/27/archives/germany-to-change-ambassadors-and-argentine-will-have-a-new.html?searchResultPosition=27 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 March 1895}}</ref><ref name=\"1895Replacement\">{{cite news |title=VON THIELMAN, GERMAN AMBASSADOR; He Takes the Place Vacated by Baron von Saurma-Jelstch. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/06/22/archives/von-thielman-german-ambassador-he-takes-the-place-vacated-by-baron.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=22 June 1895}}</ref><ref name=\"1895Surprise\">{{cite news |title=A SURPRISE FOR GERMANY; The Franco-Russian Loan to China Upsets Calculations. BERLIN FINANCIERS DISAPPOINTED Strenuous Efforts Will Be Made to Secure for Them a Large Share of the Main Indemnity Loan That China Must Negotiate. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/06/10/archives/a-surprise-for-germany-the-francorussian-loan-to-china-upsets.html?searchResultPosition=3 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 June 1895}}</ref>\n\nIn 1895, he returned to Constantinople to serve as German Ambassador to the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"Ihrig2016\"/> In his report about the treatment of the [[Armenian Genocide|Armenians]],<ref name=\"1896Warning\">{{cite news |title=GERMANY WARNS TURKEY; ATROCPTIES IN CRETE, IF CONTINUED, WILL LEAD TO TROUBLE. The Sultan Told that He May Lose the Good Will of the Powers--Demand for the Autonomy of Macedonia--The Sultan's III Health--A Woman Spendthrift--Prince Furstenberg's Illness--Another Scandal in Society. The Sultan's III Health. A Woman Spendthrift. Lenient to an Englishman. Foreigh Residents in Prussia. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1896/06/15/archives/germany-warns-turkey-atrocpties-in-crete-if-continued-will-lead-to.html?searchResultPosition=17 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 June 1896}}</ref><ref name=\"1896Armenian\">{{cite news |title=ARMENIAN HOMES BURNED; Nearly 200 Towns and Villages Destroyed in Two Provinces. THOUSANDS OF PERSONS WERE SLAIN Figures on the Destructive Work of the Turks -- The Sultan Receives Two Foreign Ambassadors. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1896/01/13/archives/armenian-homes-burned-nearly-200-towns-and-villages-destroyed-in.html?searchResultPosition=13 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=13 January 1896}}</ref> Anton:<ref name=\"Ihrig2016\">{{cite book |last1=Ihrig |first1=Stefan |title=Justifying Genocide: Germany and the Armenians from Bismark to Hitler |date=2016 |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |isbn=978-0-674-91517-6 |page=37 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Justifying_Genocide/PARuCwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Anton+Saurma+von+der+Jeltsch&pg=PA37 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\"stressed how nonsensical he found both the demonstration and the demands of the Armenians, drew particular attention to the role of the police force. He wrote that the police did not only tolerate 'that the population was massacring the Armenians, but was cheering them on and took part itself in the slaughtering of already heavily wounded and tied-up Armenians.' He also described how \"Armenians were then even 'raided and slaughtered' in their own homes.\"<ref name=\"Ihrig2016\"/></blockquote>\n\nHe was replaced in Constantinople by Baron [[Adolf Marschall von Bieberstein]], the former [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|German Minister for Foreign Affairs]], in 1897.<ref name=\"1897Post\">{{cite news |title=VON BIEBERSTEIN'S NEW POST.; The Sultan Assents to His Appointment to Succeed Baron Jeltsch. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/10/20/archives/von-biebersteins-new-post-the-sultan-assents-to-his-appointment-to.html?searchResultPosition=5 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 October 1897}}</ref><ref name=\"1897Shelved\">{{cite news |title=VON BIEBERSTEIN SHELVED.; Will Go to Turkey as Ambassador The Sultan Feels the Compliment. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1897/10/21/archives/von-bieberstein-shelved-will-go-to-turkey-as-ambassador-the-sultan.html?searchResultPosition=6 |accessdate=7 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=21 October 1897}}</ref>  From 1897 to 1899, he was the [[List of ambassadors of Germany to Italy|German Ambassador to Italy]] in [[Rome]], where he replaced [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]] who succeeded von Bieberstein as the Emporer's Minister for Foreign Affairs. Saurma von der Jeltsch retired in 1899, shortly before his death in April 1900.<ref name=\"Harrison1914\"/> \n\n==Personal life==\nAnton was married to Margarete [[House of Hatzfeld|von Hatzfeld zu Wildenburg]] (1850\u20131923), a daughter of Pauline [[House of Castellane|de Castellane]] and Count [[Max von Hatzfeld]],<ref name=\"1911Nobles\">{{cite news |last1=Diplomat |first1=A. Veteran |title=SOME EUROPEAN NOBLES THAT ARE ALMOST AMERICANS; The Family Histories of Prince Hermann Hatzfeldt and Baroness Stumm, Who Are Soon to Wed, Show Their Close Relation to This Country. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1911/03/12/archives/some-european-nobles-that-are-almost-americans-the-family-histories.html?searchResultPosition=5 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 March 1911}}</ref> who spent ten years from 1849 to 1859 as the [[List of ambassadors of Germany to France|German Minister to France]] and who signed the [[Treaty of Paris (1856)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1856 which ended the [[Crimean War]].<ref name=\"Gothaisches1906\">{{cite book |title=Gothaisches genealogisches Taschenbuch der gr\u00e4flichen H\u00e4user |date=1906 |publisher=Justus Perthes. |page=749 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4sITAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA749&lpg=PA749 |accessdate=5 May 2020 |language=de}}</ref>  After her father's death, her mother remarried to [[Louis de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]], duc de Valen\u00e7ay, 3rd duc de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord.<ref name=\"Heinemann1910\">{{cite book |last1=de) |first1=Doroth\u00e9e Dino (duchesse |title=Memoirs of the Duchesse de Dino: (afterwards Duchesse de Talleyrand Et de Sagan) 1841-1850 |date=1910 |publisher=W. Heinemann |page=372 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKNGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA372&lpg=PA372 |accessdate=5 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Her elder sister, H\u00e9l\u00e8ne, was the wife of [[Georg von Kanitz]] (''aide de camp'' to [[Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia (1828\u20131885)|Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia]]).<ref name=\"Hatzfeldt1905\">{{cite book |last1=Hatzfeldt |first1=Paul Graf von |title=The Hatzfeldt Letters: Letters of Count Paul Hatzfeldt to His Wife, Written from the Head-quarters of the King of Prussia, 1870-71 |date=1905 |publisher=John Murray |page=46 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySI_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46 |accessdate=5 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Together, they were the parents of two children:<ref name=\"Quadrangle1973\">{{cite book |title=The Book of Kings: The Families |date=1973 |publisher=Quadrangle / New York Times Book Company |isbn=978-0-8129-0280-8 |page=766 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Book_of_Kings_The_families/BF0RAQAAMAAJ |accessdate=6 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* Freiherr Maximilian Saurma von der Jeltsch (1873\u20131949), who married Anne Marie Strachwitz von Gro\u00df-Zauche und Camminetz.<ref name=\"Quadrangle1973\"/>\n* Freifrau Carmen Saurma von der Jeltsch (1875-1952), who was given a ball in Washington for her debut while her father was Ambassador.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|Among the guests at Baroness Carmen's debut at the [[Embassy of Germany, Washington, D.C.|German Embassy]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] on 8 January 1895 were the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to the United States|English Ambassador]] [[Julian Pauncefote, 1st Baron Pauncefote|Lord Pauncefort]] and Lady Pauncefote and the Misses Pauncefote, [[Hugh Gough, 3rd Viscount Gough|Hugh Gough]] and Lady Georgiana Gough (a daughter of the [[William Pakenham, 4th Earl of Longford|4th Earl of Longford]]), [[Henry Bax-Ironside|Bax Ironsides]], [[Cecil Spring Rice]], [[Mary Knowlton von Francken-Sierstorpff|Count Sierstorpff]], Baron Uechtritz, [[Salvador de Iturbide y Marz\u00e1n|Prince Iturbide]], the [[List of ambassadors of Brazil to the United States|Brazilian Minister]] and Mme. Mendon\u00e7a, the [[Turkish Ambassador to the United States|Turkish Minister]], the [[List of ambassadors of Spain to the United States|Spanish Minister]] Railie de Muruaga, and the [[List of ambassadors of Denmark to the United States|Danish Minister]] [[Constantin Brun]], the [[List of ambassadors of Italy to the United States|Italian Ambassador]] [[Saverio Fava]] and Baroness Fava, the [[Nicaragua\u2013United States relations|Nicaraguan Minister]] and Mme. Guzman, the [[List of ambassadors of the Netherlands to the United States|Netherlands Minister]] William Ferdinand Henry von Weckherlin, [[List of ambassadors of Belgium to the United States|Belgian Minister]] Count G. de Lichtervelde, and [[List of ambassadors of Sweden to the United States|Swedish Minister]] Johan Anton Wolff Grip, the [[List of ambassadors of Mexico to the United States|Mexican Minister]] [[Mat\u00edas Romero]] and Mme. Romero, Mr. and Mrs. [[Howland & Aspinwall|S. S. Howland]], [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary]] [[Hilary A. Herbert]] and Miss Herbert, Mrs. [[J. Donald Cameron|Don Cameron]] and Miss Rachel Cameron, the Misses Patten, Dr. Tavel and Mr. Vogel of the Swiss legation, [[Count Aldebert de Chambrun|Count de Chambrun]] and M. Le Favre of the [[Embassy of France, Washington, D.C.|French Embassy]], the [[List of diplomatic missions of Austria-Hungary|Austrian Minister]] [[Ladislaus Hengelm\u00fcller von Hengerv\u00e1r]] and Baroness von Hengelm\u00fcller, [[Hobart Chatfield-Taylor|Hobart]] and [[Rose Farwell Chatfield-Taylor]], Senator [[Edward O. Wolcott]] and [[Frances Metcalfe Wolcott|Mrs. Wolcott]], [[Guglielmo Imperiali|Marquis Imperiali]], Miss Biddle, [[U.S. Senator|Senator]] [[James McMillan (politician)|James McMillan]] and Mrs. and Miss McMillan, Mr. Waterbury, the Misses Boardman, [[Third Assistant Secretary of State|Assistant Secretary of State]] [[William Woodville Rockhill|Rockhill]] and Mrs. Rockhill, and Count [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Sz\u00e9chenyi|Sz\u00e9chenyi]].<ref name=\"1895Ball\"/>}}<ref name=\"1895Ball\">{{cite news |title=BARONESS VON SAURMA'S DEBUT; Grand Ball at the German Ambassador's in Washington -- The President Dines with Mr. Gresham. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1895/01/09/archives/baroness-von-saurmas-debut-grand-ball-at-the-german-ambassadors-in.html?searchResultPosition=2 |accessdate=6 May 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 January 1895}}</ref> She later married Stanislaus Graf Hoyos, Freiherr zu Stichsenstein.<ref name=\"Quadrangle1973\"/>\n\nBaron Von der Jeltsch died on 28 April 1900 in [[Chr\u00f3stnik|Brauchitschdorf]].<ref name=\"NYTObit1900\">{{cite book |title=Baron von der Jeltsch Dead. |date=1900 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1900/05/01/archives/baron-von-der-jeltsch-dead.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=6 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n;Sources\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeltsch, Anton Saurma von der}}\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:German untitled nobility]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to the Netherlands|Jeltsch]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to the United States|Jeltsch]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to Turkey|Jeltsch]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Germany to Italy|Jeltsch]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:clean up,typo(s) fixed: Emporer \u2192 Emperor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton_Saurma_von_der_Jeltsch"}
